I have problems with re-stringing tent poles with bungee cords (I’m a scout leader and tend to have to put tent poles back together all the time). What’s worked well for me is to use the plastic trimmer line from a garden trimmer or weed whacker. You can get it pretty cheap (probably have some laying around at someone’s house already) and it is stiff enough to keep a straight line. For scouts, we use really thin string or even dental floss to tie the bungee to the trimmer line but it could probably be taped together as well.

If you have a mentor who’s an electrican or know one, chances are they might have a Fish Tape that you can use to pull the rope through - of course this assumed the rope can fit through all the spaces that it need to - so watch the order of operations.

If you dont have one, alt is if you can find one of those metal coat hanger, you can ‘straighten’ one of those out enough to temp use as a fish tape and push from one way down to where the rope comes from. Tape the edge of the rope into a solid tip and tape that tip onto the end of the fish tape and pull back from the other side.

It gets tricky if you need to do any sort of tight angle/change of direction but it can be done. [and/or, pull up a ‘string’ along the rope and tape/pin it on both ends so you can use this to repull up a new rope if the rope were to break in half and you need a fast way to repull or pull up a new one].

Ok. So:

(1) What size rope? Typically teams do this with woven Dyneema. It’s thin, resists abrasion and has amazing strength for a given diameter, and has very little stretch. If you’re using something bigger, you should evaluate whether it’s too big for the extrusion you’re trying to run in.

(2) Are you mounting pulleys inside the extrusion? If so, you might need larger access holes.

(3) Try threading the rope before installing the pulleys.

One thing to think about: If you’re planning to use this design in a competition, you should know that the rope will break at the most inopportune time, when you only have 15 minutes between matches. Whatever your ultimate solution is, you should think about whether you need it to be something that you can do quickly.
